According to that, his argument would seem to have been as follows :- a slave can become free by a resolution of the people‚ without manu· mission by his dominus: consequently adrogation by his master (which took place populi auctoritate) must make him free too. But possibly Cato was thinking of the second case, which many of the older jurists regarded as quite lawful: alioquin si iuris ista antiquitas servetur, etiam servus a domino per praetorem dari in adoptionem potest, idque ait (Sabinus) plerosque iuris veteris auctores posse fieri scripsisse, Gellius 5. 19. Adoption (until justinian) involved a vindicatio, as the adoptans claimed the adoptee as his son from his present father, and we may sup- pose that the jurists referred to by Gellius inferred from this vindicatio a tacit vindicatio ‘in libertatem‚’ and treated the giving in adoption as equivalent to a manumission by vindicta. The acta intervenientia were the official records ofa magistrate or judge. Even under the Republic it had not been unusual for magis- trates to cooperate in private dispositions hy entering a minute of them in their records (gesta et acta), which entry served as irrefragable evidence of the transaction Later,a special effect was in some cases given to such entries by statute (e. g. in testaments, and in the appoint· . ment of procuratum), and after Constantine ‘insinuatio’ or entry in the acta was required by statute to give validity to many dispositions. Thus inDig. 2 4. 17 we have apud acta promittere (cf. Bk. ii. 7. 2 ins.): actis mandatum insinuare (Bk. iv. 11. 3 inf.): actorum testificatione conficere donationem (Cod. 8. 54 7): apud acta contestari (Dig. 50. 2. 7. 3) ε inter· rogari et profiteri (Cod. 7. 16. 24); and judicial appeals were also regis- tercd in the acta, apud or inter acta appellare, Dig. 49. 1. 2. 4. The right to take acta belonged to municipal magistrates (Paul. sent. rec. r. 3. r, Cod. 1. 56. 2) as well as to magistrates with jurisdiction.
